article.headline: Princeton 73, Colgate 64
article.story: PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) -- The offensive force that Princeton junior center Judson Wallace became at the end of last season has carried over to the 2003-04 campaign. Wallace scored 19 of his career-high 28 points in the second half and added a team-high 11 rebounds to lead Princeton to a 73-64 win over Colgate in its season opener last night in Princeton. Wallace scored 22 or more points in four of Princeton's last five games when the Tigers finished 16-11 a year ago. Princeton may depend even more on Wallace's output this season, something Princeton coach John Thompson III wasn't sure he wanted to see. "Judson played well. It's essential in our setting because the center position is the hub of what we do," said Thompson. "But some games (the box score) is going to look like 28 points and 11 rebounds and others it will be 10-12-14 points, 10 rebounds and more than the two assists he had tonight. He has to make the team better." Wallace scored eight of his points as Princeton opened the second half with a 17-4 run to build its biggest lead of 21 at 51-30 with 14:44 left in the game, and it appeared the Tigers would coast the rest of the way. But Colgate (0-1) responded by hitting 14 of 16 free throws after the intermission to spark a 26-10 spurt that drew the Raiders to within 61-56 with 3:59 left. Howard Blue led the charge by scoring 14 of his team-high 23 in the second half. Princeton was up to the challenge, however, as senior Konrad Wysocki scored in the lane and Wallace added a free throw to push the lead back to eight with 2:28 left. Wallace was confident and wanted to be the difference maker when the game was on the line. "I definitely want the ball when it's tight and my teammates were able to get it to me," Wallace said. The Tigers, who opened at home for the first time in nine years, enjoyed a 34-24 lead at the half, behind Wallace's nine points, five rebounds and two assists. Wallace drilled a 3-pointer from the left wing to make it 23-15 and, after a score by Colgate's Mark Linebaugh, Wallace hit a reverse layup. Wysocki, who had nine points in the half, drove for a layup to build the lead to 10 for the first time. The half was marred by poor foul shooting by both teams, which combined for 2-of-14 from the line.
